<p>Guidelines about what to say and how to say it.</p>

<h2 id="aperture-science-products">Aperture Science products</h2>

<h3 id="latency-and-uptime">Latency and uptime<br /></h3>
<p>Donâ€™t make specific promises about latency, uptime, or related topics in public-facing documentation. These details should be reserved for SLAs and contracts.</p>

<h3 id="unrealistic-claims">Unrealistic claims<br /></h3>
<p>Donâ€™t make unsubstantiated or unrealistic claims about Aperture Science, including who we are, what we do, the services we offer, or how our products work.</p>

<h3 id="unreleased-products">Unreleased products<br /></h3>
<p>Donâ€™t mention unreleased products or features in public-facing documentation.</p>

<h2 id="tone">Tone</h2>

<h3 id="be-friendly">Be friendly<br /></h3>
<p>Strive for an approachable, friendly toneâ€”polished, professional, but not excessively formal.</p>

<h3 id="write-for-non-experts">Write for non-experts<br /></h3>
<p>Write in a way thatâ€™s easy for most people to understand, even if the reader isnâ€™t an expert in a given topic. A good rule of thumb: estimate the expertise of your average reader, then write for an audience with slightly less expertise than that.</p>

<h2 id="word-choice">Word choice</h2>

<h3 id="filler-words">Filler words<br /></h3>
<p>Avoid filler words like <em>very.</em> Rather than describing a task as <em>very important</em>, you might say that itâ€™s <em>critical</em>.</p>

<h3 id="simple-vs-complex">Simple vs. complex<br /></h3>
<p>When possible, try to use short, simple words instead of complex, abstract words.</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Weak:</strong> This setting facilitates data filtering.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Strong:</strong> This setting lets you filter data.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>However, if thereâ€™s no way to avoid using complicated words or technical jargon, itâ€™s often helpful to give a definition, include <a href="/styleguidetemplate/dev/tone-and-content/formatting-and-organization/#links">a hyperlink</a> to related materials, or provide other additional context.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Example:</strong> Be careful not to cross the black holeâ€™s event horizon. An event horizon is the point at which an objectâ€™s gravity becomes too strong to escapeâ€”if you cross the event horizon, youâ€™ll never come back.</li>
</ul>

